== Awareness all inclusive

If you don't like enumerations, I apologize in advance. These were ways for people to keep track of the teachings before they wrote them down, and it's quite useful as a memory device, mnemonics and things. So of course, with the five aggregates you have form, feelings, perception, mental formations, and conditioned consciousness. So to me, it's always been a strange list because it intertwines and people tend to treat them as they're different or separate even.

And so conditioned consciousness has to be there in form. We would consider the body form, and it's living intelligence. It's alive; it's consciousness. Wounds can heal themselves and the heart is beating all by itself right now and taking care of all your blood for you. No problem. There's intelligence there. The breathing is happening, all that. So we can logically and perhaps even scientifically conclude that there is living intelligence throughout the body. So form is living intelligence.

And then also empty space, even if you want to reduce this completely to our most subtle forms that we have here in our environment. Space is also alive, has these quantum fields right? With quantum noise. So truly fascinating stuff, every object that you see has a life to it. It's living; there's interaction, luminosity, play, luminosity. Light is bouncing around and we're indulging in it.

So form, feelings. What feelings do we have right now? Are we feeling hot, neutral, cold, angry, passive, happy? There are all kinds of things: worried, fearful, aggressive, powerful, confident, insecure---so many things that feelings, combined with form now and conditioned consciousness, lead to a _perspective_, the third of the aggregates. 

So now it's almost like you have a pristine glass of water and you've added a little bit of flavoring into it now, that's your perspective. And these can be very subtle, you know, we can even have a Buddhist perspective or a Dzogchen perspective, walk around with this perspective.

And the good thing is, is it's permeated by what? What permeates our perspectives---which is our conditioned consciousness---permeating our feelings and our mental formation? Anyone know the one ingredient that's consistent in all of those?

Awareness. Don't be afraid to say it. 

We want to keep it simple. We want to make it comprehensive. So we have these: form, feelings, perspective, mental formations, and any conditioned consciousness. So maybe I'm in a mood right now, right? I'm in some kind of predisposition, or just a position of some sorts. Well, then, that is conditioned consciousness. I have to hold that in place with a thought, with some kind of habitual absorption, self-absorption or contraction---I always say psychic contraction.

And so now perhaps I heard some news earlier that there's somebody around giving money to everybody. And so I come here into meditation and I think, "I wonder where that person is right now. I wonder what time they'll be out tomorrow." And you see, and then I talk to you all and I say, "How's it going everybody?" But I have this predisposition of, man, I want to meet this... I want to find this person tomorrow who's giving away all the money." And that's the flavoring that I've added to my pristine water. That's my perspective then. And it's sort of a subtle hiding.

And this happens with all kinds of stuff: political affiliation, religious affiliation. These things can make us get a subtle superiority complex, right? When we're a certain religion and we think that we got it, but the other people don't got it. Right? And we don't praise them anymore as Buddhas or unique teachers or anything like that; we just see them below us because they don't got it.

Oh, that's no way to live; we all know that's not... that's a spell. That's a curse that we get under when we start to believe that, because we have this religious disposition or even with Dzogchen, that we are somehow superior, or better, or know something that other people don't know. You could just be way behind, you could be one of the only ones that needs Dzogchen; the other people don't even need it. We never know, really, we never know.

So we see reality as our teacher. We saw these people as, you know, co-emergent aspects of mind with profound depth beyond our surface imputations and coarse narratives. It becomes very beautiful like that; it opens up. And so, the five aggregates begin to soften up. You know, obviously the three spheres of conception are in there---this subject, action, object trichotomy.

That's right, I'm hitting you with the enumerations today! We're going to talk about the one path (the Ekayana), the two truths, the three poisons, the four noble truths, the five aggregates, the six perfections, the seven points of postures, the eightfold path, nine yanas, the ten virtues. Of course, I could go on, but then your head will explode. And we're not going to talk about all that today, okay? Don't worry. But as you can see, there are a lot of enumerations in the Dharma.

Dawai reading and responding to chat: That's a different religion, but sure. It just comes in like, "What about the ten chicken nuggets I had in my McDonald's? Oh my goodness, okay. All good.

Dawai: So the four foundations of mindfulness are included in that too, right? Another enumeration. But it's very useful because it's like knowing your car mechanics when you have these lists and you have these labels that you can utilize because you're already subscribing to them. You're already labeling this stuff, this random aggregate of energy, or this contraction of energy or consciousness. You're already labeling that. So it's working with what you're already doing, not creating any new labels. 

So we have these thoughts, feelings, the body, and the environment as the four foundations of mindfulness, also permeated by awareness, okay?
So there's an underlying theme here that I'm pushing---that everything is included within awareness, that we don't need to get anywhere else or activate it. It's naturally already there. 

So let's go over the 80 states of consciousness, okay? And think: there are 33 related to aversion, 40 to attachment, and seven to ignorance. Me going through these can be like me just pointing you to, you know, "There's your battery, there's your alternator, etc. There's your spark plugs, and there's where your gas goes; there's where your oil goes." You know, just naming things that are going on in our mechanics and our awareness. 

