Dawai: Well yeah, we have this limited nomenclature, right? Our semantics are quite limited, comparatively speaking, to some of these other languages and the depth of psychology that they had in the Dharma. So I notice repeats in terms that are very reductive. And so yeah basically, we could say that it's a diverse word right there. Detachment can be very nuanced there. And I don't know what standard detachment would be. Detachment is never really a positive thing. I don't want to... you know, the lack of grasping is not the same as detachment here. I think you may be referring to lack of grasping.

Sangha 1: Yeah, that's what I was thinking about.

Dawai: Yeah, and here I think... which is good that you're bringing that up because it's a good distinction. Here, detachment is not related, in my opinion, to the relief of grasping, because that's when then we're talking about liberation, we're not talking about 80 conditioned states anymore. We're talking about self liberation there. That _taṇhā_. So yeah, and then detachment can work in many ways as in a sort of aversion, right? It's under aversion? That makes sense. Okay, very good. Anything else then?

I think I really sent it home here with a lot of emphasis. We tend to think, "oh, this feeling I'm having right now, this is not Buddhahood, this is not enlightenment, and this is not meditation." Right? But the very mind that seeks some other state is the great perfection. That's why we gotta come home. Rather than trying to get somewhere else, we're already home.

But there are thresholds that we need to cross, everybody. It may be some depression, it may be some heavy stuff, it may be urges to smoke or drink or something like that. And you catch yourself smoking and drinking, even though you don't want it.

But then when they run out, and maybe you just go out one day without a drink---then you're starting to cross the threshold. You're feeling that feeling of wanting a drink. You're letting that come and go with an awareness. And so now you're crossing the threshold into a great peace, independent of having to drink or smoke or anything. You found it because you were able to wade through that threshold.

That makes sense, right? Because that's what's capturing all of us, anybody, is that there's just a point that we can't... we can't be with that. We need to go pass out, we need to go eat, we need to go take a walk or run or something, right? Anything not to be with this right now. So, that's why I always say baby steps.

But if I have an impulse right now to smoke some crack, taking a funny example, nobody really smokes crack anymore, right? So I can use that one now safely? It's a dad joke. So I'm using this as an example. So I have the impulse to go smoke crack. But I don't do it. I sit here. Within five or ten minutes, that impulse goes away and I've overcome, at least that time. Maybe it'll come back, but it's gonna be weaker next time. And then eventually it'll be gone if I can keep doing that.

So not only are we sitting through urges to smoke or eat some food, but we're sitting through the conditioned self arising and apprehending things. We're sitting through karmic tendencies and impulses, patterns that have been accumulated through beginningless time over lifetimes. They are now allowed to come up and fly freely without risk of being shot down and trapped in the cage of evaluation and analysis. Now we can let our experience be no matter what it is, all 80 of them. Making sense, yeah? Did you want to join in?

