Dawai: Oh know we brought that up the other day. Yeah, there could be some pretty substantial so-called darkness that comes up for you until you can walk through demons, right? There's like having a dream of the scariest thing that you could imagine, but this time, instead of it taking you aback, now you're actually just walking straight through that thing---that image, that appearance that used to scare you so much. 

And so, this is what---where dreams and dream science can be a great indicator of one's liberation. Are the appearances still fooling you? Are they still captivating? And so, things will arise: empty things, bananas. They to nothing, but we take them to be something. And it could be heavy bouts of desire, anger, confusion, restlessness.

I'm preparing many of you to where you will not have to go through it like I went through it, or I've seen other people go through it. The degree of awareness, sangha support, scriptures you have access to. all in one library---it's not going to be that damn dark. 

You know, you have the right text when you need it. You can ask questions when you need to. You have people around. You have daily sessions for comfort and to socialize. We need that. We need that love. We need the Little Bear to appear once a day, once or twice a day, right in the middle of the camera. "Hi, buddy. Hi." Oh, didn't come at the perfect time, right? When we're talking about communion and friendship.

It really is a huge factor, everybody, you know, in our Dharma trip. And to me, it was heartbreaking seeing how many people were left alone on this trip. They're given these powerful teachings and everything and then left alone, abandoned, or got some powerful empowerment and see their guru once in a blue moon. Right? If they're even lucky. "Hi, Little Bear. [dog] I know, I agree with you; totally 100% agree with you, right now. Okay? We're in agreement."

But yeah, so this tended to be a Western anomaly that started to take place, a lack of communion. People were getting compartmentalized and very lonely. And that's what started this whole session in 2013---these online gatherings, Meditation Online---was that I saw that. I thought, That's not how it's supposed to be; we're supposed to be in touch with each other.
We're a sangha here. We practice the same stuff. We know the same teachers and all this.

And that also gives me huge incentive to be more skillful and use reflection, correction---part of awareness---to allow it to continue to make me more skillful at hosting; just to be able to present the Dharma and keep the safe space safe. Right? So there was a lot to learn in that. So anyway, "dark night of the soul" will maybe be a little bit less dramatic for anybody associated, affiliated with these gatherings, in my opinion. That's the entire point of them.


